<b>Rouille</b> (<language wordnetid="106282651" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../597/10597.xml">
French</link></language>
, '<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../477/26477.xml">
rust</link>') is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../937/61937.xml">
sauce</link> that consists of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../478/22478.xml">
olive oil</link> with <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../062/1277062.xml">
breadcrumb</link>s, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../469/50469.xml">
garlic</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../332/53332.xml">
saffron</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../225/74225.xml">
chili pepper</link>s. <ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref> It is served as a garnish with <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../587/4699587.xml">
fish</link>, fish <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../298/19651298.xml">
soup</link> and, notably, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../584/767584.xml">
bouillabaisse</link>. Rouille is most often used in the cuisine of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../503/48503.xml">
Provence</link>.
